@page "/explainer"
@inject IJSRuntime JS

<h1 class="page-title">The maths, in detail</h1>
<p class="page-intro">
    The full walkthrough behind the <a href="/">simulator</a>: the Vietoris–Rips
    complex, the filtration, homology and Betti numbers, why this app computes
    over <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/2"></span>, the boundary-matrix pairing
    algorithm, and the persistence diagram's stability guarantee.
</p>

<section class="explainer">
    <h2>What is this?</h2>
    <p>
        Sample some points off a shape — say, a wobbly circle. Around every
        point, grow a disc of radius <span data-katex="\varepsilon/2"></span>.
        For small <span data-katex="\varepsilon"></span> the discs are tiny
        and disjoint: just confetti. Make <span data-katex="\varepsilon"></span>
        huge and everything overlaps into one blob. Somewhere in between, the
        discs merge into a ring with an empty middle — the circle's hole is
        unmistakable. <strong>Persistent homology is the bookkeeping of that
        movie</strong>: which pieces and holes exist at which radius, and how
        long each one survives.
    </p>

    <h2>Growing balls: the Vietoris–Rips complex</h2>
    <p>
        At radius <span data-katex="\varepsilon"></span>, connect two points
        with an edge whenever their discs touch, and fill in a triangle
        whenever three points are all mutually close. Formally, this is the
        <strong>Vietoris–Rips complex</strong>:
    </p>
    <div data-katex="\mathrm{VR}_\varepsilon(X) \;=\; \{\,\sigma \subseteq X \;:\; \operatorname{diam}(\sigma) \le \varepsilon\,\}"
         data-katex-display></div>
    <p>
        every subset of points whose diameter — its largest pairwise distance
        — is at most <span data-katex="\varepsilon"></span> becomes a simplex.
        This app builds it up to triangles (dimension 2), which is all that's
        needed to see pieces and loops.
    </p>

    <h2>A movie of complexes: the filtration</h2>
    <p>
        As <span data-katex="\varepsilon"></span> grows, every complex
        contains the previous one —
    </p>
    <div data-katex="\mathrm{VR}_{\varepsilon}(X) \;\subseteq\; \mathrm{VR}_{\varepsilon'}(X) \quad \text{for } \varepsilon \le \varepsilon'"
         data-katex-display></div>
    <p>
        — so nothing already built is ever removed. This nested sequence is
        the <strong>filtration</strong>. Features are born when a piece
        splits off or a loop first closes, and die when they merge away or
        get filled in; the barcode is just this movie, flattened onto one
        axis.
    </p>

    <h2>Counting pieces and holes: homology</h2>
    <p>
        Homology makes "pieces" and "holes" precise. Working over
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/2"></span> (so a chain is just a set of
        simplices, and adding a simplex twice cancels it), the boundary of a
        triangle is the sum of its three edges,
    </p>
    <div data-katex="\partial_2[abc] \;=\; [ab] + [bc] + [ac] \pmod 2" data-katex-display></div>
    <p>
        and homology in dimension <span data-katex="k"></span> is the cycles
        that aren't themselves a boundary of anything one dimension up:
    </p>
    <div data-katex="H_k \;=\; \ker \partial_k \,/\, \operatorname{im} \partial_{k+1}" data-katex-display></div>
    <p>
        Its rank is the <strong>Betti number</strong> <span data-katex="\beta_k"></span>
        — <span data-katex="\beta_0"></span> counts pieces,
        <span data-katex="\beta_1"></span> counts loops, the
        <strong>one-dimensional holes</strong> bounded by edges rather than
        surfaces, which is exactly what the "pieces" and "holes" readouts on
        the simulator show at the current <span data-katex="\varepsilon"></span>.
        Higher <span data-katex="\beta_k"></span> counts
        higher-dimensional holes: <span data-katex="\beta_2"></span> is a
        cavity enclosed by a shell of triangles rather than a loop of edges —
        the hollow inside a football, not a ring. A standard example is the
        <strong>torus</strong> (the surface of a doughnut), which has
        <span data-katex="\beta_0=1"></span> (it's one piece),
        <span data-katex="\beta_1=2"></span> (two independent loops that
        can't be shrunk to a point or filled in — one running round the tube,
        one round the central hole) and <span data-katex="\beta_2=1"></span>
        (the cavity its surface encloses). This app only builds the complex
        up to triangles, so <span data-katex="k \le 1"></span> is all it can
        ever detect — a torus point cloud would show up here only through
        its two <span data-katex="\beta_1"></span> loops, with the
        <span data-katex="\beta_2"></span> cavity invisible to it.
    </p>

    <h2>A note on coefficients: why <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/2"></span>?</h2>
    <p>
        Homology can be computed with coefficients in any abelian group, not
        just <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/2"></span> — the integers
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}"></span> or the reals
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{R}"></span> work too, and the results are
        related by the <strong>Universal Coefficient Theorem</strong>:
    </p>
    <div data-katex="H_k(X; G) \;\cong\; \big(H_k(X;\mathbb{Z}) \otimes G\big) \;\oplus\; \operatorname{Tor}\big(H_{k-1}(X;\mathbb{Z}), G\big)"
         data-katex-display></div>
    <p>
        The first term is the "expected" rank; the <span data-katex="\operatorname{Tor}"></span>
        term is a correction that only kicks in when the integral homology one
        dimension down has <em>torsion</em> — a finite cyclic piece such as
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/n"></span> rather than a free
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}"></span>. Real-valued coefficients
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{R}"></span> kill all torsion outright
        (<span data-katex="\operatorname{Tor}(\mathbb{Z}/n, \mathbb{R}) = 0"></span>
        for every <span data-katex="n"></span>), so an <span data-katex="\mathbb{R}"></span>-computed
        Betti number can only ever be <em>smaller</em> than or equal to a
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/2"></span>-computed one. The textbook
        example is the real projective plane: its integral
        <span data-katex="H_1 = \mathbb{Z}/2"></span> is invisible to
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{R}"></span> coefficients entirely, yet that
        same torsion resurfaces one dimension up as an honest
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/2"></span> class in
        <span data-katex="H_2(X; \mathbb{Z}/2)"></span>. This app uses
        <span data-katex="\mathbb{Z}/2"></span> for a purely practical reason:
        every simplex's boundary is just "which faces", with no signs or
        orientations to track, which is exactly what the reduction algorithm
        below needs. For the pieces and loops these presets produce, that
        choice essentially never changes the count — the caveat above is
        about when, in principle, it could.
    </p>

    <h2>How to read the barcode</h2>
    <p>
        Every bar is one feature: a connected piece
        (<span data-katex="H_0"></span>) or a
        one-dimensional hole — a loop (<span data-katex="H_1"></span>). A bar
        spans exactly the range of <span data-katex="\varepsilon"></span>
        where that feature exists — it appears at its <em>birth</em> radius
        and disappears at its <em>death</em> radius, where it merges into a
        bigger piece or gets filled in by triangles.
        <strong>Short bars are noise; long bars are real shape.</strong> The
        vertical sweep line is "now" — wherever the ε slider currently sits.
        Hover a bar to see exactly which piece or hole it is, traced directly
        on the point cloud.
    </p>

    <h2>Births, deaths, and the pairing algorithm</h2>
    <p>
        Every bar comes from a linear-algebra fact: writing the boundary maps
        as matrices, there's a way to reduce them,
    </p>
    <div data-katex="R \;=\; \partial\, V" data-katex-display></div>
    <p>
        so that each column of the reduced matrix <span data-katex="R"></span>
        either vanishes (its simplex is a birth) or points back to exactly one
        earlier simplex (its death partner) — that's the pairing algorithm
        this app runs on every point-cloud edit. The cycle it highlights when
        you hover a bar <em>is</em> that reduced column, read back as points
        and edges.
    </p>

    <h2>The persistence diagram</h2>
    <p>
        Tick <strong>Persistence diagram</strong> to see the same births and
        deaths plotted as points instead of bars: birth on one axis, death on
        the other. A point's distance from the diagonal is its lifetime —
        points hugging the diagonal are the short, noisy bars; points far
        above it are the long, real ones.
    </p>

    <h2>Advanced: stability</h2>
    <p>
        This view earns its keep through a stability guarantee: nudging the
        point cloud by at most <span data-katex="\delta"></span> (in
        Hausdorff distance) moves every point in the diagram by at most
    </p>
    <div data-katex="d_{\mathrm B}\big(\mathrm{Dgm}(X), \mathrm{Dgm}(Y)\big) \;\le\; 2\, d_{\mathrm H}(X, Y)" data-katex-display></div>
    <p>
        Try it: drag the noise slider on a noisy circle and watch the one
        long bar barely move while the short ones jitter. That robustness —
        small perturbations can only cause small changes to the diagram — is
        the whole reason persistent homology is used on real, noisy data:
        sensor readings, images, biological measurements, anywhere the "true"
        shape is hidden under jitter.
    </p>
</section>

@code {
    protected override async Task OnAfterRenderAsync(bool firstRender)
    {
        if (firstRender) await JS.InvokeVoidAsync("renderKatex");
    }
}
